<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>GR-4 Systems of Linear Equations</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers systems of linear equations. You should be able to solve systems of linear 
      equations using various methods such as substitution and elimination. You should also be able 
      to determine the number of solutions to a system of linear equations and interpret the solutions 
      in context.
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
        <li><p>Basics of Graphing: Give a graph with appropriate scales and labels. The line should have the 
          correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>Solve a two-variable system of linear equations using substitution.</p></li>
      <li><p>Solve a two-variable system of linear equations using elimination.</p></li>
      <li><p>Solve a three-variable system of linear equations using elimination.</p></li>
      <li><p>Determine if a system of linear equations has no solution, one solution, or infinitely many 
        solutions.</p></li>
      <li><p>Solve a nonlinear system of equations using substitution or elimination.</p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
        <statement><p>Solve the system using substitution: 
        <m>\begin{cases} 2x + y = 5 \\ 3x - 2y = 8 \end{cases}</m></p></statement>
        <hint><p>Rewrite the first equation to express y in terms of x. Then 
          substitute this expression into the second equation.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\left(\frac{18}{7}, -\frac{1}{7}\right)</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>First, solve the first equation for y: <m>y = 5 - 2x</m>. 
          Then substitute this into the second equation: <m>3x - 2(5 - 2x) = 8</m>. 
          Simplify: <m>3x - 10 + 4x = 8</m>. Combine like terms: <m>7x = 18</m>. 
          Solve for x: <m>x = \frac{18}{7}</m>. Finally, substitute back to find 
          y: 
          <md><mrow>y &amp; = 5 - 2 \cdot \frac{18}{7}</mrow>> 
            <mrow> &amp;= 5 - \frac{36}{7}\\ \amp = \frac{35 - 36}{7}</mrow> 
            <mrow> &amp; = -\frac{1}{7}</mrow></md></p></solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise workspace="3cm">
          <statement><p>Solve the system using elimination: 
            <md><mrow>\begin{cases} 4x-3y=12</mrow>
              <mrow>3x+2y=13 \end{cases}</mrow></md></p></statement>
          <hint><p>Multiply the first equation by 2 and the second equation 
            by 3 to eliminate y.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>\left(\frac{63}{17}, \frac{4}{17}\right)</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>Multiply the first equation by 2: <m>8x - 6y = 24</m>. 
            Multiply the second equation by 3: <m>9x + 6y = 39</m>. Add the 
            two equations: <m>17x = 63</m>. Solve for x: <m>x = \frac{63}{17}</m>. 
            Substitute back into the first equation: 
            <m>4\left(\frac{63}{17}\right) - 3y = 12</m>. Simplify: 
            <m>\frac{252}{17} - 3y = 12</m>. Solve for y: <m>y = \frac{4}{17}</m>.</p></solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise workspace="3cm">
          <statement><p>Solve the system using elimination:
            <m>\begin{cases} 2x+y-z=4\\ x-2y+3z=-6\\ 3x+y+2z=7 \end{cases}</m></p></statement>
          <hint><p>Pick a base equation to use for eliminating the same variable in the 
            other two equations. Solve the resulting two-variable system.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>\left(\frac{3}{14}, \frac{9}{2}, \frac{13}{14}\right)</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>Let the second equation be the base equation. Multiply it by 2 and 
            subtract it from the first equation to eliminate x: <m>5y - 7z = 16</m>. 
            Multiply the second equation by 3 and subtract it from the third equation to 
            eliminate x: <m>7y - 7z = 25</m>. Solve the resulting two-variable system for y 
            and z. We can use elimination to find y, by subtracting the first equation 
            from the second: <m>y = \frac{9}{2}</m>. Substitute this to find the value of z.
            <m>z=\frac{13}{14}</m>. Substitute these values back into the base equation 
            to find x: <m>x-2\left(\frac{9}{2}\right)+3\left(\frac{13}{14}\right)=-6</m>.
           Solving for x we get <m>x = \frac{3}{14}</m>.</p></solution>
      </exercise>
      <exercise workspace="3cm">
          <statement><p>Find all solutions to the system:
            <m>\begin{cases} \frac{4}{x^2}+\frac{6}{y^4}=\frac{7}{2}\\\frac{1}{x^2}-\frac{2}{y^4}=0\end{cases}</m></p></statement>
          <hint><p>Use substitution to solve for one variable in terms of the other.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>\left(-\sqrt{2}, -\sqrt{2}\right), \left(\sqrt{2}, \sqrt{2}\right), 
            \left(-\sqrt{2}, \sqrt{2}\right), \left(\sqrt{2}, -\sqrt{2}\right)</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>Here we can use substitution. From the second equation, we have 
            <m>\frac{1}{x^2} = \frac{2}{y^4}</m>. Substituting this into the first equation 
            gives us <m>4 \cdot \frac{2}{y^4} + \frac{6}{y^4} = \frac{7}{2}</m>. Simplifying, 
            we get <m>\frac{14}{y^4} = \frac{7}{2}</m>. Solving for <m>y^4</m>, we find 
            <m>y^4 = 4</m>, so <m>y = \pm \sqrt{2}</m>. Substituting back into the 
            second equation, we can find the corresponding values of <m>x</m>. So 
            <m>x = \pm \sqrt{2}</m>.</p></solution>
      </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet> 
